<paragraph id="F77124697E68FFF193AF278FFCE5FB67" blockId="4.[151,1436,730,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis id="C5BAF87B7E68FFF193AF278FFEB6FC01" bold="true" box="[199,316,904,927]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="30CE5FEA7E68FFF1922A2780FD8CFC01" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2017" box="[322,518,903,927]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atrax" subSpecies="vargai">
<emphasis id="C5BAF87B7E68FFF1922A2780FD8CFC01" box="[322,518,903,927]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Polia atrax vargai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF1917D278FFD02FC01" box="[533,648,904,927]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1933,1955]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,1166,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1162,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Polia spp., males, adults. 9. P. atrax vargai. HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 10. P. atrax vargai, PT, China, Gansu, (MDS); 11. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 12. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847470/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Figs. 9, 10</figureCitation>
) can be separated from the nominotypical subspecies (
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF197BB278FFADBFC01" box="[1235,1361,904,927]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1933,1955]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,1166,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1162,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Polia spp., males, adults. 9. P. atrax vargai. HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 10. P. atrax vargai, PT, China, Gansu, (MDS); 11. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 12. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847470/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
) by its significantly lighter, fawn coloured – pale hazel brown or pale grayish body vesture and forewing ground colour, somewhere with reddish brown suffusion; the light brown, brown, somewhere reddish brown, contrasting forewing pattern and the lighter hindwings. In the nominotypical subspecies, the body vesture and forewing ground colour and the forewing pattern conspicuously darker, dark brown (in the more than eighty years old 
<typeStatus id="28759ACB7E68FFF1972F2015FB2EFBB7" box="[1095,1188,1042,1065]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF197DC2015FA88FBB7" box="[1204,1282,1042,1065]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1933,1955]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,1166,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1162,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Polia spp., males, adults. 9. P. atrax vargai. HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 10. P. atrax vargai, PT, China, Gansu, (MDS); 11. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 12. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847470/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) light greyish brown), thus forewing seems to be more homogenous, the forewing pattern less contrasting, the cross lines hardly discernible. The comparison of the male genitalia of the two subspecies (
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF190A5205FFB10FBF1" box="[973,1178,1112,1135]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 21" captionStartId="7.[151,258,1981,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,232,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,221,1925]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 21. Polia atrax male genitalia. 19. P. atrax vargai, HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 20. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 21. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847476/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Figs. 19 &amp; 20, 21</figureCitation>
) indicates some slight, however well recognizable differences, which provide enough evidence to the authors to describe here the new taxa on subspecific level. The 
<taxonomicName id="30CE5FEA7E68FFF192E4209AFDA4FB2A" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2017" box="[396,558,1181,1204]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atrax" subSpecies="vargai">
<emphasis id="C5BAF87B7E68FFF192E4209AFDA4FB2A" box="[396,558,1181,1204]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">P. atrax vargai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have much larger tuft appendage on the basal part of the left saccular extension (which is triangle in the 
<taxonomicName id="30CE5FEA7E68FFF192C020C7FDB5FB49" authority="atrax" box="[424,575,1216,1239]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atrax" subSpecies="atrax">
<emphasis id="C5BAF87B7E68FFF192C020C7FDB5FB49" box="[424,575,1216,1239]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">P. atrax atrax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), weaker, shorter right saccular extension, longer cucullus ”neck” and smaller cucullus; the terminal cornuti field in the vesica is somewhat longer.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F77124697E68FFF193AF2102FE43FA82" blockId="4.[151,1436,730,2036]" box="[199,457,1285,1308]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">The female is unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BFD477E27E68FFF193AF212FFCE1F812" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" type="description">
<paragraph id="F77124697E68FFF193AF212FFCE1F812" blockId="4.[151,1436,730,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis id="C5BAF87B7E68FFF193AF212FFEC1FAA1" bold="true" box="[199,331,1320,1343]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Description</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF19234212FFE59FAA1" box="[348,467,1320,1343]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1933,1955]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,1166,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1162,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Polia spp., males, adults. 9. P. atrax vargai. HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 10. P. atrax vargai, PT, China, Gansu, (MDS); 11. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 12. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847470/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Figs. 9, 10</figureCitation>
) Wingspan 
<quantity id="3036898C7E68FFF19131212FFD5AFAA1" box="[601,720,1320,1343]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="5.2" metricValueMin="4.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" unit="mm" value="49.0" valueMax="52.0" valueMin="46.0">46–52 mm</quantity>
, length of forewing 
<quantity id="3036898C7E68FFF190DA212FFBA1FAA1" box="[946,1067,1320,1343]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" unit="mm" value="23.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="22.0">22–25 mm</quantity>
. Antennae brown, filiform, finely ciliated. Vesture of the thorax hazel brown, or grayish hairs brown tipped, while of the abdomen somewhat lighter. The forewing elongated with pointed apex. Ground colour fawn coloured–pale hazel brown, somewhere reddish brown suffused, or pale grey. The wings pattern conspicuous, light brown, brown, somewhere reddish brown. The transversal lines well discernible, particularly the double, zigzagged basal and antemedial lines, while the postmedial line simple, arched, crenellated; the subterminal line brown, zigzagged, with 4–5 brown small arrowhead–like patches on the inner side; the terminal line black, fine, slightly wavy, with some black dots inward. Hindwings pale brown coloured, with broad but diffuse darker marginal field; the cellular discal spot is a fine, curved brown line. The most remarkable features of the new subspecies in the male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="6FF538EC7E68FFF19101223AFD3FF9CA" box="[617,693,1597,1620]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 21" captionStartId="7.[151,258,1981,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,232,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,221,1925]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 21. Polia atrax male genitalia. 19. P. atrax vargai, HT, China, Gansu, PGY 4631 m (PGM / HNHM); 20. P. atrax atrax, HT, China, N. Yunnan, VZ 8945 m (ZFMK); 21. P. atrax atrax, China, N. Yunnan, PGY 4444 m (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847476/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) are as follows: the rather short and almost evenly thin uncus; slightly developed, elongated tegumen; dorsally tapering, elongated juxta, U–shaped vinculum; short, thin, finger–like, somewhat evenly curved harpe on a broad, somewhat bifurcate base; almost evenly broad valve, distally with a narrow “neck”, joining with the triangular strongly haired cucullus, with slight corona and a single cornutus in the ventral angle. The most conspicuous features are the long, asymmetric saccular extensions, with long, strong hairs terminally and large conical tuft on the left side, while the asymmetric smaller tufts of which the right one is much more developed, are situated on the medial part of the sacculus. The sclerotized aedeagus evenly ventrally curved, with thorn–like strongly sclerotized carinal plate; vesica membranous, ample, distally tubular, dorsally recurved with a large, prominent, conical medial and a less conspicuous subbasal diverticulum and a long terminal cornuti field; almost oppositely, an elongated, thin sclerotized field may be present, which absents in the 
<typeStatus id="28759ACB7E68FFF1906E2372FCEDF812" box="[774,871,1909,1932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BFD477E27E68FFF193AF239FFB10F86A" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="F77124697E68FFF193AF239FFB10F86A" blockId="4.[151,1436,730,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">
